{"title_page": "Colorado's 2nd Senate district", "text_new": "{{Short description|American legislative district}}\n{{Infobox legislative district\n|state=Colorado\n|district=2\n|chamber=Senate\n|image=[[File:Colorado Senate District 2 (2010).png|350px]]\n|representative=[[Dennis Hisey]]\n|party=Republican\n|residence=Ca\u00f1on City\n|Democratic=18.3\n|Republican=40.8\n|NPP=38.9\n|percent_white=78\n|percent_black=4\n|percent_hispanic=13\n|percent_asian=1\n|percent_native_american=1\n|percent_pacific_islander=1\n|percent_other_race=3\n|percent_remainder_of_multiracial=\n|population=153,388<ref name=\"Census\">{{Cite web|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/61000US08002-state-senate-district-2-co/|title=State Senate District 2, CO|publisher=Census Reporter|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|population_year=2018\n|voting_age=\n|citizen_voting_age=\n|registered=111,657<ref name=\"Reg\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/VoterRegNumbers/2020/March/VotersBySenateDist.pdf|title=Total Registered Voters by State Senate District, Party, and Status|website=|publisher=Colorado Secretary of State|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|notes=\n}}\n'''[[Colorado]]'s 2nd Senate district''' is one of 35 districts in the [[Colorado Senate]]. It has been represented by [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Dennis Hisey]] since 2019, succeeding fellow Republican [[Kevin Grantham]].<ref name=\"CO Site\">{{Cite web|url=https://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/dennis-hisey|title=Senator Dennis Hisey |publisher=Colorado General Assembly|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nDistrict 2 covers suburbs and exurbs of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]] and other parts of central Colorado, including all of [[Clear Creek County, Colorado|Clear Creek]], [[Fremont County, Colorado|Fremont]], [[Park County, Colorado|Park]], and [[Teller County, Colorado|Teller Counties]] and parts of [[El Paso County, Colorado|El Paso County]]. Communities in the district include [[Idaho Springs, Colorado|Idaho Springs]], [[Georgetown, Colorado|Georgetown]], [[Fairplay, Colorado|Fairplay]], [[Ca\u00f1on City, Colorado|Ca\u00f1on City]], [[Florence, Colorado|Florence]], [[Lincoln Park, Colorado|Lincoln Park]], [[Penrose, Colorado|Penrose]], [[Cripple Creek, Colorado|Cripple Creek]], [[Woodland Park, Colorado|Woodland Park]], [[Fountain, Colorado|Fountain]], [[Cascade-Chipita Park, Colorado|Cascade-Chipita Park]], [[Ellicott, Colorado|Ellicott]], [[Fort Carson]], and parts of [[Security-Widefield, Colorado|Security-Widefield]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://redistricting.colorado.gov/final-plans-approved-court|title=Final Plans Approved by the Court |publisher=Colorado Redistricting - General Assembly|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe district overlaps with Colorado's [[Colorado's 2nd congressional district|2nd]] and [[Colorado's 5th congressional district|5th congressional districts]], and with the 13th, 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st, 39th, 47th, and 60th districts of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2019/7/30/1848730/-How-do-counties-House-districts-and-legislative-districts-all-overlap-These-new-tools-show-you|author=David Jarman|title=How do counties, House districts, and legislative districts all overlap?|publisher=Daily Kos|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recent election results==\nColorado Senators are elected to staggered four-year terms; under normal circumstances, the 2nd district holds elections in midterm years.\n===2018===\n{{Election box open primary begin no change| title= [[2018 Colorado State Senate election]], District 2<ref name=\"Ballotpedia\">{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_District_2|title=Colorado State Senate District 2|publisher=Ballotpedia|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate