ln Park, Colorado|Lincoln Park]], [[Penrose, Colorado|Penrose]], [[Cripple Creek, Colorado|Cripple Creek]], [[Woodland Park, Colorado|Woodland Park]], [[Fountain, Colorado|Fountain]], [[Cascade-Chipita Park, Colorado|Cascade-Chipita Park]], [[Ellicott, Colorado|Ellicott]], [[Fort Carson]], and parts of [[Security-Widefield, Colorado|Security-Widefield]].<ref name=\"CO Site\"/><ref name=\"Reg\"/>\n\nThe district overlaps with Colorado's [[Colorado's 2nd congressional district|2nd]] and [[Colorado's 5th congressional district|5th congressional districts]], and with the 13th, 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st, 39th, 47th, and 60th districts of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2019/7/30/1848730/-How-do-counties-House-districts-and-legislative-districts-all-overlap-These-new-tools-show-you|author=David Jarman|title=How do counties, House districts, and legislative districts all overlap?|publisher=Daily Kos|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recent election results==\nColorado Senators are elected to staggered four-year terms; under normal circumstances, the 2nd district holds elections in midterm years.\n===2018===\n{{Election box open primary begin no change| title= [[2018 Colorado State Senate election]], District 2<ref name=\"Ballotpedia\">{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Colorado_State_Senate_District_2|title=Colorado State Senate District 2|publisher=Ballotpedia|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate  = [[Dennis Hisey]]\n | votes      = 12,818\n | percentage = 57.9\n | change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate  = Stephanie Luck\n | votes      = 9,302\n | percentage = 42.1\n | change     = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n | votes      = 22,120\n | percentage = 100\n | change     = \n}}\n{{E